  "text": "Django's admin filter rendering pipeline controls filter visibility through the `has_output()` method. Here's the complete chain:\n\n1. **Filter Base Class** (`django/contrib/admin/filters.py` lines 26-75): The `ListFilter` base class defines the `has_output()` method (lines 41-47) as an abstract method that subclasses must implement. This method determines whether a filter should be displayed.\n\n2. **Related Field Filter** (`django/contrib/admin/filters.py` lines 222-323): The `RelatedFieldListFilter` class extends `FieldListFilter` and implements `has_output()` (lines 248-253). For related ForeignKey fields, it returns `True` only if there is more than one choice available (considering the extra empty choice for nullable fields): `return len(self.lookup_choices) + extra > 1`\n\n3. **ChangeList Filter Collection** (`django/contrib/admin/views/main.py` lines 175-277): The `ChangeList.get_filters()` method collects all filters and applies the visibility filter. At line 221, it checks `if spec and spec.has_output():` before adding the filter spec to `filter_specs`. This means filters that return `False` from `has_output()` are excluded from the rendered filter list.\n\n4. **Template Tag Rendering** (`django/contrib/admin/templatetags/admin_list.py` lines 520-529): The `admin_list_filter` template tag renders individual filter specs by calling `spec.choices(cl)` to get the filter choices.\n\n5. **Template Iteration** (`django/contrib/admin/templates/admin/change_list.html` line 72): The change_list template iterates over the pre-filtered `cl.filter_specs` list using `{% for spec in cl.filter_specs %}{% admin_list_filter cl spec %}{% endfor %}`. By this point, empty filters have already been excluded by the `has_output()` check in `ChangeList.get_filters()`.\n\nThe critical control point is `ChangeList.get_filters()` which filters specs based on `has_output()` before they reach the template, ensuring only filters with actual output are rendered in the admin sidebar."
}

